Pull request description:

  Guix recently force pushed to their `version-1.4.0` branch, causing #24040. At the time #24042 pointed to the newest commit on that branch, fixing #24040, but it didn't actually build. Guix have now [temporarily removed](https://lists.gnu.org/archive/html/guix-devel/2022-01/msg00313.html) their `version-1.4.0` branch, while they incorporate additional fixes.

  This PR updates our guix time-machine to point to a recent commit on the guix master branch, so that builds can resume for all hosts apart from Windows. Windows builds are broken due to what looks like an upstream issue, which  results in e failure to build the [`mingw-w64-x86_64-winpthreads package`](https://git.savannah.gnu.org/cgit/guix.git/tree/gnu/packages/mingw.scm#n137). The build fails with:
  ```bash
  /gnu/store/4y5m9lb8k3qkb1y9m02sw9w9a6hacd16-bash-minimal-5.1.8/bin/bash ./libtool  --tag=CC   --mode=link x86_64-w64-mingw32-gcc -Wall -DWIN32_LEAN_AND_MEAN -g -O2 -no-undefined -version-info 1:0:0 -L./fakelib -Wc,-no-pthread  -o libwinpthread.la -rpath /gnu/store/2bglap5gk4db8lajaahg4d7361myw5qw-mingw-w64-x86_64-winpthreads-8.0.0/lib src/libwinpthread_la-barrier.lo src/libwinpthread_la-cond.lo src/libwinpthread_la-misc.lo src/libwinpthread_la-mutex.lo src/libwinpthread_la-rwlock.lo src/libwinpthread_la-spinlock.lo src/libwinpthread_la-thread.lo src/libwinpthread_la-ref.lo src/libwinpthread_la-sem.lo src/libwinpthread_la-sched.lo src/libwinpthread_la-clock.lo src/libwinpthread_la-nanosleep.lo src/version.lo
  libtool: link: x86_64-w64-mingw32-gcc -shared  src/.libs/libwinpthread_la-barrier.o src/.libs/libwinpthread_la-cond.o src/.libs/libwinpthread_la-misc.o src/.libs/libwinpthread_la-mutex.o src/.libs/libwinpthread_la-rwlock.o src/.libs/libwinpthread_la-spinlock.o src/.libs/libwinpthread_la-thread.o src/.libs/libwinpthread_la-ref.o src/.libs/libwinpthread_la-sem.o src/.libs/libwinpthread_la-sched.o src/.libs/libwinpthread_la-clock.o src/.libs/libwinpthread_la-nanosleep.o src/.libs/version.o   -L./fakelib  -g -O2 -no-pthread   -o .libs/libwinpthread-1.dll -Wl,--enable-auto-image-base -Xlinker --out-implib -Xlinker .libs/libwinpthread.dll.a
  x86_64-w64-mingw32-ld: final link failed: bad value
  collect2: error: ld returned 1 exit status
  ```

  This info will be sent upstream. You can likely recreate the failure with `guix build mingw-w64-x86_64-winpthreads`.

  Once Guix is at a point of tagging a 1.4.0 release commit (after re-branching and RCs), we can shift our time-machine to point to it. If a change is made upstream in relation to the Windows issue we are seeing, we will adjust our time-machine commit earlier.

UI 746 refactor swapper/web3 into services (#958)

* Add skeleton of service

* In progress code, before changing SwapToken amount type

* Refactor Swapper/web3 Into Services

- Create Swap service that holds most of the logic that swapper used to
do.
- Create new SwapToken type that can work for both swapIn and swapOut
methods to avoid duplication.
- Create services for accessing each of the different solidity
contracts, so that it is clear what contracts are being called with what
parameters.
- Create Contract Caller service that is similar to web3 with cleaner
code and less parameters required.
- Add new method to gas price service to generate gas price overrides
when calling contracts.

* Cleanup network and address code

- Remove all initialization of network and addresses from service
constructors.
- Remove all contract / signer related code from services as they all go
through contract-caller now.
- Pull network / address dynamically through the config service instead,
so it's always up to date.

* Remove unused vars from vault service

* Code Style + Type Fixes

- Use an enum for SwapToken type instead of a string.
- Use strict equality everywhere
- Remove unneccessary async's
- Add types to returns from Functions.

* Move ContractCaller to web3, general code cleanup

- Move the contractCaller to services/web3 as it has similar contract
interaction functionality and is similar to the old web3 util.
- Make GasSettings an interface.
- Don't use composables in services
- Fix bugs in gas price service.

* Add setting of web3 service provider

- Allow setting the provider of the web3 service so that swapper can set
it to the user wallet provider before performing a swap. This is so
address retrieval and sendTransaction calls are done via the users
wallet rather than infura.
- Fixed bug with vault abi.

* Add a reactive provider to web3.service

* Add computed provider to web3.service.ts

- Make web3.plugin.ts pass a computed function into the service that
determines the correct provider to use when the service is used. The
provider is set whenever a new wallet is connected and automatically
reacts to the account being changed.

* Remove network/provider being passed to swapper

- These are now unneccessary as the provider is automatically set in
web3.service.ts.

* Use dependency injection for services, add appProvider and userProvider

- Services should keep their own readonly local pointer to services so
they can be changed via dependency injection if required.
- Have separate appProvider and userProvider in the web3 service
that are used in different locations.

* Add exchange proxy tests. Add Address type.

- Add basic tests for exchange proxy
- Add Address type which is a string, to be more explicit about what
artugments should be Addresses and what should be numbers.

* Apply SOR v2 updates

- Apply all updates to support SORV2 that are already in develop

* Add Vault Service tests

- Add vault service tests
- Change some exports to export class as default

* Change variable name to userProvider

* Add unit tests for swap service

- Add unit tests for single, multi and lido swaps, ensuring they call
the correct services with the correct arguments
- Create mocks for services to use in tests.

* Fix linter issues

* Fix bug with tokenIn/tokenOut being changed in lidoBatchSwap

- Fix bug with those token details being changed because they are passed by
reference.
- Fix swap tests.

* Lint fixes

* Fix Bugs with Native Asset Swapping, Lido Swapping

- Fixed bug where native asset value wasn't being passed through to
service.
- Fixed bug with lido tests where the tokenIn.address wasn't lowercase
so stETH wasn't being converted to wstETH
- Added tests for fixes.
- Added more types to ABI's

* Remove unused var, rebase

* Fix minor issues with ENS avatars after rebase

* Move Boosted Pool swap functions to swap.service

- Move boostedJoinBatchSwap and boostedExitBatchSwap from swapper to
swap.service. Use vault service for performing the swaps.

* Reverse ens and avatar order to be same as before

* Re-add console logs for web3 call information

* Add unit tests for boosted pool invest/withdraw

* Refactor boostedJoin to use SwapTokens as arguments

- Update boostedJoinBatchSwap to take SwapToken's instead of what they
were taking previously
- Update test to call with new arguments, but keep rest of the test the
same.

* Refactored boostedExitBatchSwap to use SwapTokens

- Refactored boostedExitBatchSwap to use SwapTokens like the other
functions
- Update tests and swapper to use these new arguments and ensure it
still works as it should.

* Refactor calcaulateLimits and use for boosted pools

- Refactor calculateLimits so that it can take arrays of tokens.
- Reduce duplicate code in calculateLimits and boosted pools. Use
calculateLimits to generate the limits for boosted pools.

* Rename MetamaskError to WalletError

* Use SwapV2 from sdk instead of sor2

*always* have at least one element. If the string is empty, the
array will be [""], so we need to check [1] == "" instead of
checking a length of zero.

Hodler Coalition Coin

Use HEAD instead of GITHUB_SHA to diff master and PR

- Using "${GITHUB_SHA}" to point to the pull request commit does not work when
  the pull request comes from a fork. The incorrect SHA leads to the diff being
  incorrect, which leads to validation errors. Using HEAD eliminates these
  problems, diffing the correct states.
